## 2. Identified Problems

### 🔴 Critical Issues

#### P1: Broken Sync Pipeline (Import References Don't Exist)

[ojs-sync-cron.ts](../scripts/ojs-sync-cron.ts) imports from paths that do not exist:

```typescript
import { getActiveJournals, getPublishedArticles } from '../lib/ojs-service';  // ❌ Does not exist
import { closeOJSConnection, testOJSConnection } from '../lib/ojs-client';     // ❌ Does not exist
```

The actual OJS client lives at [src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts) and exports different functions ([ojsQuery](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts#54-98), [isOjsConfigured](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts#8-15), [ojsHealthCheck](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts#143-170), [closeOjsPool](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts#171-180)). **The sync cron job is completely non-functional.**

#### P2: Two Competing Integration Strategies (Architectural Split-Brain)

The [.env.production.template](../.env.production.template) documents two strategies:
- **Option A:** HTTP Proxy via PHP (`OJS_API_URL` + `OJS_API_KEY`)
- **Option B:** Direct MySQL (`OJS_DATABASE_*`)

The runtime code exclusively uses **Option B** (direct MySQL via [ojs-client.ts](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts)), but [.env](../.env) still has both sets of credentials. The PHP proxy architecture ([debug.php](../submit_manger_api/debug.php), `config.php`, `api.php`, `.htaccess`) was designed but the Node.js consumer for it was never implemented. This creates confusion about which path is canonical.

#### P3: No User Identity Mapping Between Systems

DigiPub has its own `admin_users` table (Prisma), while OJS has its own `users` table. There is:
- No shared user ID strategy
- No SSO or token federation
- No FK relationship or mapping table
- No way to correlate a DigiPub admin with their OJS counterpart

Authors, reviewers, and editors exist only in OJS. When DigiPub eventually needs to display reviewer assignments or author profiles, there is no identity bridge.

#### P4: Raw Credentials in [.env](../.env) and Source Control

The [.env](../.env) file contains plaintext production database credentials for the OJS remote database on SiteGround:
```
OJS_DATABASE_HOST="<REDACTED>"
OJS_DATABASE_PASSWORD="<REDACTED>"
```
And admin passwords:
```
ADMIN_PASSWORD="<REDACTED>"
SUPPORT_PASSWORD="<REDACTED>"
```

> [!CAUTION]
> These credentials are checked into the repository and visible in git history. They must be rotated immediately.

---

### 🟡 Significant Issues

#### P5: Duplicate Type Definitions

Two separate type definitions for OJS journals exist:
- [types/ojs-type.ts](../src/features/ojs/types/ojs-type.ts) – manual TypeScript interfaces (missing `thumbnail_url`)
- [schemas/ojs-schema.ts](../src/features/ojs/schemas/ojs-schema.ts) – Zod schemas (includes `thumbnail_url`)

The [index.ts](../src/features/ojs/index.ts) re-exports from [types/ojs-type.ts](../src/features/ojs/types/ojs-type.ts), but the server route uses [schemas/ojs-schema.ts](../src/features/ojs/schemas/ojs-schema.ts). Consumers receive different type shapes depending on which import they use.

#### P6: Hardcoded Submit Manager URL

The OJS base URL is hardcoded in the route handler:
```typescript
const baseUrl = "https://submitmanager.com"  // ojs/server/route.ts:44
```
And in [debug.php](../submit_manger_api/debug.php):
```php
$siteBaseUrl = rtrim($config['site_base_url'] ?? 'https://submitmanager.com', '/');
```
This should be an environment variable.

#### P7: Cross-Host MySQL Without IP Whitelisting Guarantee

The DigiPub server on Hostinger connects to MySQL on SiteGround. This requires:
1. SiteGround Remote MySQL to be enabled
2. Hostinger's outbound IP to be whitelisted

Hostinger's IP can change on shared hosting. If it changes, **all OJS data disappears from the homepage** with no user-visible error — only a 500 in the API that the frontend swallows to show an empty state (`{ success: true, data: [], configured: false }`).

#### P8: Sync Script Uses Raw SQL Instead of Prisma

The sync cron uses `prisma.$executeRaw` and `prisma.$queryRaw` for the DigiPub database, bypassing Prisma's type safety and the model layer:
```typescript
await prisma.$executeRaw`INSERT INTO journals (...) VALUES (...) ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE ...`;
```
This duplicates schema logic and can silently break if the Prisma schema changes.

#### P9: Missing `submission_id` FK in Sync Articles

The [syncArticles()](../scripts/ojs-sync-cron.ts#103-169) function inserts into `published_articles` without a required `submission_id`:
```sql
INSERT INTO published_articles (journal_id, doi, publication_date, ojs_publication_id, created_at)
```
But the Prisma schema requires `submission_id` as a non-nullable FK. This query will always fail.

#### P10: In-Memory Cache Without Invalidation

The OJS route handler uses a simple JS-object cache:
```typescript
const cache = {
    journals: { data: null as any, expiresAt: 0 },
    stats: { data: null as any, expiresAt: 0 }
}
```

In a multi-instance deployment or serverless environment, this cache is per-process and uncoordinated. No manual invalidation endpoint exists. If OJS data is updated, users must wait up to 5 minutes.

#### P11: SSL Configuration Bypasses Certificate Verification

```typescript
ssl: { rejectUnauthorized: false, minVersion: 'TLSv1.2' }
```
This makes the connection vulnerable to MITM attacks.

---

### 🟠 Moderate Issues

#### P12: Dual DB Init Mechanisms

Two separate database initialization flows exist:
1. [server.js](../server.js) — uses `execSync('npx prisma db push')` + `execSync('npx prisma db seed')`
2. [instrumentation.ts](../instrumentation.ts) → [lib/db/init.ts](../lib/db/init.ts) — uses `spawn('npx prisma migrate deploy')` + Prisma Client seeding

Both run on startup. The [instrumentation.ts](../instrumentation.ts) path is the Next.js-recommended approach; [server.js](../server.js) is a legacy path. They can race or conflict.

#### P13: JWT Secret Weakness

```
JWT_SECRET="your_jwt_secret_here_change_in_production"
```
The development [.env](../.env) has a placeholder that could accidentally ship to production. The 7-day expiry with no refresh token mechanism means a stolen token grants 7 days of access.

#### P14: No Rate Limiting on OJS Endpoints

The `/api/ojs/*` endpoints have no rate limiting. A bot could flood these endpoints, which in turn would exhaust the 3-connection MySQL pool to SiteGround.

#### P15: Hono RPC Client Cast to `any`

```typescript
export const client = hc<AppType>(`${baseUrl}/api`) as any
```
This eliminates type safety for all frontend API calls. Any breaking API change will not be caught at compile time.

---

## 3. Root Cause Analysis

```mermaid
graph TD
    RC1["No formal integration contract<br/>between DigiPub ↔ OJS"] --> P1 & P2 & P3
    RC2["Incremental ad-hoc development<br/>without architectural oversight"] --> P5 & P6 & P8 & P12 & P15
    RC3["Credentials management<br/>not formalized"] --> P4 & P13
    RC4["Hosting constraints not<br/>formally documented"] --> P7 & P11
    RC5["Sync module developed<br/>against phantom API"] --> P1 & P9
    
    style RC1 fill:#7f1d1d,stroke:#f87171,color:#fecaca
    style RC2 fill:#78350f,stroke:#fbbf24,color:#fef3c7
    style RC3 fill:#7f1d1d,stroke:#f87171,color:#fecaca
    style RC4 fill:#78350f,stroke:#fbbf24,color:#fef3c7
    style RC5 fill:#7f1d1d,stroke:#f87171,color:#fecaca
```

| Root Cause | Impact | Problems |
|------------|--------|----------|
| No integration contract between DigiPub and OJS | Every integration is ad-hoc; changes in OJS silently break DigiPub | P1, P2, P3 |
| Incremental development without architectural review | Duplicate code, competing strategies, dead code paths | P5, P6, P8, P12, P15 |
| No secrets management discipline | Production credentials in source code | P4, P13 |
| Hosting constraints undocumented | Fragile cross-host MySQL; no failover | P7, P11 |
| Sync module developed against phantom API | Entire cron job is dead code | P1, P9 |

