## 4. Proposed Architecture

### 4.1 Target Architecture

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph DigiPub["DigiPub — Hostinger"]
        NX["Next.js 16 SSR"]
        HONO["Hono API"]
        OIL["OJS Integration Layer"]
        PRISMA["Prisma ORM"]
        DDB[("DigiPub DB")]
        CACHE["Cache Layer"]
    end

    subgraph Bridge["Integration Bridge — SiteGround"]
        PHPAPI["PHP REST API<br/>(api.php + router)"]
    end

    subgraph OJS["Submit Manager — SiteGround"]
        OJSAPP["OJS Application"]
        OJSDB[("OJS DB")]
    end

    Browser -->|HTTPS| NX
    NX --> HONO --> OIL
    OIL -->|HTTP/REST| PHPAPI
    PHPAPI -->|localhost MySQL| OJSDB
    HONO --> PRISMA --> DDB
    OIL --> CACHE
    OJSAPP --> OJSDB
    
    style PHPAPI fill:#065f46,stroke:#34d399,color:#d1fae5
    style OIL fill:#1e3a5f,stroke:#38bdf8,color:#e2e8f0
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key architectural decision:** Replace the cross-host direct MySQL connection with a PHP REST API bridge on SiteGround. This eliminates the IP whitelisting dependency, improves security (no remote MySQL credentials in DigiPub), and provides a stable contract boundary.

### 4.2 Integration Layer Design

#### PHP API Bridge (SiteGround side)

Deploy a minimal PHP REST API on SiteGround that:
1. Runs on the same host as OJS → connects to MySQL via `localhost`
2. Authenticates requests via API key in `X-API-KEY` header
3. Exposes read-only endpoints: `/journals`, `/stats`, `/health`, `/articles`
4. Returns clean JSON — handles PHP serialized data parsing server-side
5. Rate limits per IP

#### Node.js OJS Client (DigiPub side)

Replace the direct MySQL client with an HTTP client:

| Current ([ojs-client.ts](../src/features/ojs/server/ojs-client.ts)) | Proposed (`ojs-http-client.ts`) |
|---|---|
| `mysql2/promise` pool | [fetch()](../src/features/ojs/server/route.ts#18-48) with retry |
| 3 connections to remote MySQL | HTTP to PHP bridge |
| SSL with `rejectUnauthorized: false` | Standard HTTPS |
| Connection pool management | Stateless HTTP |
| DNS/TCP health checks | HTTP health endpoint |

### 4.3 Database Integration Strategy

**Principle:** Each system owns its database exclusively. No cross-database writes.

| Data | Owned by | Consumed by | Sync strategy |
|------|----------|-------------|---------------|
| Journals metadata | OJS | DigiPub | Pull via API, cache 5 min |
| Submissions | OJS | DigiPub | Pull via API on demand |
| Published articles | OJS | DigiPub | Pull via API + periodic sync |
| Platform stats | OJS | DigiPub | Pull via API, cache 5 min |
| Admin users | DigiPub | DigiPub only | No sync needed |
| Messages, FAQ | DigiPub | DigiPub only | No sync needed |

### 4.4 User Identity Mapping

**Phase 1 (minimal):** Add an `ojs_user_id` column to `admin_users`:
```prisma
model AdminUser {
  // ... existing fields
  ojs_user_id  BigInt?  @unique
}
```

**Phase 2 (SSO):** Implement token-based SSO where DigiPub issues JWTs that OJS validates via a plugin.

### 4.5 Error Handling Strategy

| Scenario | Current behavior | Proposed behavior |
|----------|-----------------|-------------------|
| OJS DB unreachable | Silent empty response | Return cached data + `stale: true` flag; log alert |
| API bridge 5xx | N/A (no bridge) | Retry 3× with backoff; fall back to cached |
| Sync job fails | `process.exit(1)` | Log to `system_settings`, alert via webhook, retry |
| Malformed OJS data | Zod throws, 500 | Log + skip bad record, return valid records |

